13:31.352 --> 13:33.330
- Is that it? We're close?
- Hey, I don't want to either.

13:33.354 --> 13:35.273
- But shouldn't we?
- Dave: Well, do we have to?

13:35.356 --> 13:38.609
Well, not good, Bryce. Okay?

13:38.693 --> 13:40.778
Me and Amanda are not good. It's not good.

13:40.862 --> 13:42.113
Bryce: Are you at fault?

13:42.196 --> 13:43.966
No, it was her fault.
She made me text her coworker.

13:43.990 --> 13:45.950
Yeah, fucking of course
it's my fault, bro.

13:46.034 --> 13:47.243
I'm an asshole.

13:47.326 --> 13:48.578
Well, at least we have work.

13:48.661 --> 13:50.621
- Dave: And money.
- To work and money.

13:50.705 --> 13:52.040
- Dave: Yeah, baby.
- Yeah, baby.

13:52.123 --> 13:53.291
We're pathetic, aren't we?

13:53.374 --> 13:55.094
Soren: Oh, my god, dude.
Somebody, shoot us.

13:56.210 --> 13:58.963
(Both speaking Spanish)

13:59.464 --> 14:00.899
Felicity: (In English)
No, I'm not gonna have...

14:00.923 --> 14:02.484
Jesus Christ. I want to live
inside this thing.

14:02.508 --> 14:06.596
Mmm. So it's okay
that I'm not as into this as you are?

14:06.679 --> 14:07.722
Oh, no, no. It's good.

14:07.805 --> 14:09.390
I'm sitting with the coolest girl here.

14:09.474 --> 14:11.559
Okay, so what is it with this food thing?

14:12.101 --> 14:14.896
I don't know. It's like,
you know how people idolize,

14:14.979 --> 14:16.522
you know, athletes, and musicians,

14:16.606 --> 14:18.399
- and painters, and stuff?
- Mmm-hmm.

14:18.483 --> 14:20.753
Yeah, those people are idiots.
What they do, it doesn't matter.

14:20.777 --> 14:23.362
They play with inflatable balls
and ukuleles and shit.

14:23.446 --> 14:24.655
Chefs,

14:24.739 --> 14:26.991
they play with the raw materials
of life itself.

14:27.492 --> 14:28.743
And death itself. It's...

14:29.494 --> 14:32.955
I mean, I've watched every fucking episode
of <i>chef's table</i> two or three times.

14:33.039 --> 14:34.791
I've watched slowik's 20 times.

14:34.874 --> 14:38.961
I've watched him explain the exact moment
a green strawberry is perfectly unripe.

14:39.045 --> 14:40.922
I've watched him plate a raw scallop

14:41.005 --> 14:43.424
during its last
dying contraction of muscle.

14:43.508 --> 14:45.343
It's art on the edge of the abyss,

14:45.426 --> 14:47.428
which is where god works, too.
It's the same.

14:47.512 --> 14:49.263
That was beautifully put, Tyler.

14:49.347 --> 14:51.224
- Stop. Don't. No.
- No! I'm being serious.

14:51.307 --> 14:54.644
I think I'm, um, starting to get it.

14:54.727 --> 14:56.437
- Really?
- Yeah. A little.

15:02.443 --> 15:04.445
(Bell dings)

15:06.823 --> 15:09.450
(Suspenseful music playing)

15:16.791 --> 15:18.126
Okay.

15:18.209 --> 15:19.252
Yes, chef.

15:20.169 --> 15:21.587
(Classical music playing)

15:35.268 --> 15:36.394
(Classical music fades)

15:44.944 --> 15:45.945
Slowik: Good evening.

15:46.404 --> 15:47.488
Good evening.

15:47.572 --> 15:49.092
- Good evening. Hello.
- George: Hello.

15:50.199 --> 15:51.492
Welcome to hawthorn.

15:52.201 --> 15:53.536
I am Julian slowik,

15:53.619 --> 15:56.080
and tonight it'll be
our pleasure to feed you.

15:56.164 --> 15:57.415
The curtain rises.

15:57.874 --> 16:01.836
Slowik: Over the next few hours
you will ingest fat,

16:02.336 --> 16:05.882
salt, sugar, protein,

16:06.382 --> 16:08.885
bacteria, fungi,

16:09.635 --> 16:11.512
various plants and animals,

16:11.596 --> 16:14.724
and, at times, entire ecosystems.

16:15.641 --> 16:18.644
But I have to beg of you one thing.

16:18.728 --> 16:19.729
It's just one.

16:20.438 --> 16:22.481
Do not eat.

16:23.524 --> 16:24.609
Is he serious?

16:25.234 --> 16:26.235
Taste.

16:28.070 --> 16:29.238
Savor.

16:29.322 --> 16:30.323
Relish.

16:31.199 --> 16:34.076
Consider every morsel
that you place inside your mouth.

16:36.204 --> 16:37.246
Be mindful.

16:38.206 --> 16:39.624
But do not eat.

16:40.958 --> 16:44.128
Our menu is too precious
for that. (Chuckles softly)

16:44.212 --> 16:45.338
And look around you.

16:45.630 --> 16:48.216
Here we are on this island.

16:49.383 --> 16:50.384
Accept.

16:51.844 --> 16:53.137
Accept all of it.

16:54.055 --> 16:56.265
And forgive.

16:58.142 --> 16:59.518
And on that note,

17:00.394 --> 17:01.395
food!

17:01.979 --> 17:03.940
George: Yeah, yeah. Bring it, bring it.

17:05.273 --> 17:06.525
Here they come.

17:07.777 --> 17:10.320
Lillian: Oh, wow.
It's like a marching band.

17:13.782 --> 17:16.953
Slowik: Our first course
is called "the island."

17:17.036 --> 17:19.372
On your plate are plants
from around the island,

17:19.454 --> 17:21.540
placed on rocks from the shore,

17:21.624 --> 17:24.252
covered in barely frozen,
filtered seawater

17:24.335 --> 17:26.796
which will flavor the dish as it melts.

17:27.296 --> 17:29.024
You know, this is what the guy
was fishing for earlier...

17:29.048 --> 17:30.049
Slowik: Sorry?

17:31.384 --> 17:32.468
Tyler: Um...

17:33.261 --> 17:34.262
Sorry, chef.

17:35.888 --> 17:38.724
It's perfectly all right.
Yes, they are those very same scallops.

17:39.558 --> 17:42.186
Now, here is what you must
remember about this dish.

17:42.853 --> 17:46.190
We, the people on this island,
are not important.

17:47.275 --> 17:51.821
The island and the nutrients it provides
exist in their most perfect state

17:52.321 --> 17:56.909
without us gathering them
or manipulating them, or digesting them.

17:57.368 --> 18:00.871
What happens inside this room
is meaningless

18:00.955 --> 18:03.999
compared to what happens
outside in nature,

18:04.625 --> 18:06.585
in the soil, in the water,

18:07.211 --> 18:08.254
in the air.

18:09.880 --> 18:12.967
We are but a frightened nanosecond.

18:15.052 --> 18:16.971
Nature is timeless.

18:19.390 --> 18:20.391
Enjoy.

18:21.267 --> 18:22.685
(Guests clapping)

18:22.768 --> 18:23.894
That's a cheery thought.

18:24.729 --> 18:25.730
(Sniffles)

18:27.440 --> 18:28.649
Are you crying?

18:29.608 --> 18:32.737
It's just that I find it all very moving.

18:32.820 --> 18:34.238
It's all so beautiful. I just...

18:34.780 --> 18:36.240
It's almost too beautiful to eat.

18:37.408 --> 18:39.219
- (Phone camera shutter clicking)
- Margot: You know,

18:39.243 --> 18:41.203
the nicest restaurant
in my hometown was...

18:41.287 --> 18:42.887
You don't think chef's mad at me, right?

18:43.873 --> 18:44.915
For the scallop thing?

18:44.999 --> 18:47.001
You don't have to call him "chef," Tyler.

18:47.084 --> 18:49.420
I'm pretty sure he doesn't even know
about your existence.

18:49.503 --> 18:50.880
I kind of want him to...

18:51.297 --> 18:53.966
- Like you? (Chuckles)
- Yeah. Kinda.

18:54.050 --> 18:55.343
Tyler, you're the customer.

18:55.426 --> 18:57.303
You're paying him to serve you.

18:57.928 --> 19:00.306
It doesn't really matter
whether he likes you or not.

19:00.389 --> 19:01.724
Right. Wait. What does that mean?

19:01.807 --> 19:02.933
Mmm. Nothing.

19:03.476 --> 19:05.853
Relax. Just eat your rock.

19:05.936 --> 19:08.564
And to pair, from our friends
at Caroline morey,

19:08.647 --> 19:10.232
a chassagne-montrachet

19:10.858 --> 19:12.902
premier cru from 2014.

19:13.361 --> 19:15.154
Not just a single vineyard.

19:15.237 --> 19:17.198
A single row of vines.

19:17.281 --> 19:18.949
- Wow. Perfect.
- It's magical.

19:19.617 --> 19:21.994
Ted: Thoughts?
I'm really feeling this is quite...

19:22.078 --> 19:24.246
It's half-great. It's there in moments.

19:24.330 --> 19:25.331
There in moments.

19:25.414 --> 19:27.249
There's a neediness
to the plating, you know.

19:27.333 --> 19:28.773
I mean, it's been tweezered to fuck.

19:28.834 --> 19:31.128
But the flavors are there.
It's very clean.

19:31.212 --> 19:33.339
It's very, um, thalassic.

19:34.548 --> 19:36.258
- "Thalassic?"
- oceanic.

19:36.342 --> 19:38.177
Thalassa was the primeval
spirit of the sea.

19:38.260 --> 19:39.387
Oh, thalassa and pontus.

19:39.470 --> 19:41.263
- Yes, yes, yes.
- Correct. So, we are...

19:43.057 --> 19:44.558
We're eating the ocean.

19:45.476 --> 19:46.852
We're eating the ocean.

19:46.936 --> 19:48.312
- Yeah.
- Yes.

19:51.690 --> 19:53.192
- Felicity: How is it?
- Mmm.

19:54.193 --> 19:55.194
It's good.

19:55.277 --> 19:57.381
You can't just say "good"
for the show. You have to...

19:57.405 --> 19:58.614
You have to embellish.

19:59.573 --> 20:01.593
Oh, my god. For crying out loud.
It's not brain surgery, okay?

20:01.617 --> 20:03.887
- It's a goddamn travel-food show.
- I know. Okay, so then, do it.

20:03.911 --> 20:06.414
Yeah, yeah. So pitch it to me.

20:06.497 --> 20:08.617
- Okay, so we go to Italy, right?
- Felicity: Mmm-hmm.

20:08.916 --> 20:13.212
We shoot me in Capri pants
on a pastel green Vespa,

20:13.295 --> 20:16.590
driving around to get
to some giuseppe's farm with cheese.

20:16.674 --> 20:19.051
I eat the cheese, and then...

20:19.135 --> 20:20.344
There's a close-up of me.

20:20.428 --> 20:24.223
And I close my eyes, and I fake an orgasm,
and then off to South Africa,

20:24.306 --> 20:28.018
and then, I maybe...
I talk about how racism is not so cool,

20:28.102 --> 20:29.979
and bingo bongo, Emmy time.

20:30.062 --> 20:31.289
- That's it?
- Okay? Can I eat now?

20:31.313 --> 20:33.583
That's what you're gonna pitch
to three streaming services on Monday?

20:33.607 --> 20:34.668
Yeah. Pretty much. That's that.

20:34.692 --> 20:36.652
Yeah. Jesus fucking Christ.
That's a disaster.

20:36.735 --> 20:38.946
I don't think you can go
to South Africa with a dui.

20:39.572 --> 20:41.740
- Soren: You like this?
- The otter food?

20:41.824 --> 20:42.992
Yeah. It's solid.

20:43.075 --> 20:44.511
Soren: I mean,
I've had shellfish just as good

20:44.535 --> 20:47.121
with my chef at home, Ricardo.
You know Ricardo. He's amazing.

20:47.204 --> 20:48.581
Bryce: Incredible.
Soren: Whatever.

20:48.664 --> 20:50.344
At least we can say
we've been here, right?

20:50.749 --> 20:52.710
My dad used to say
that you buy the experience.

20:53.836 --> 20:57.173
Richard: I mean, this looks like
a suburban landscaping.

20:57.631 --> 20:58.632
What the fuck?

21:01.844 --> 21:04.221
I saw Perry at delaurenti's the other day.

21:09.643 --> 21:10.644
Oh?

21:12.855 --> 21:13.856
How is he?

21:15.941 --> 21:16.942
You know...

21:17.443 --> 21:18.486
Perry.

21:22.531 --> 21:23.574
Thank you.

21:26.869 --> 21:28.496
Slowik: I want plating in five!

21:28.579 --> 21:29.788
Cooking team: Yes, chef!

21:35.586 --> 21:36.921
(Bell dings)

21:41.800 --> 21:42.801
(Claps)

21:43.886 --> 21:45.012
Is he gonna keep doing that?

21:45.846 --> 21:50.684
Bread has existed in some form
for over 12,000 years,

21:51.477 --> 21:53.020
especially amongst the poor.

21:54.230 --> 21:55.272
Flour and water.

21:55.898 --> 21:56.982
What could be simpler?

21:57.316 --> 22:02.571
Even today, grain represents
65% of all agriculture.

22:03.489 --> 22:05.824
Fruits and vegetables only 6%.

22:06.784 --> 22:12.373
Ancient Greek peasants dipped their stale,
measly bread in wine for breakfast.

22:13.332 --> 22:15.709
And how did Jesus teach us to pray

22:15.793 --> 22:18.420
- if not to beg for our daily bread?
- Beg for our daily bread.

22:19.088 --> 22:22.967
It is, and has always been,
the food of the common man.

22:23.509 --> 22:27.137
But you, my dear guests,
are not the common man.

22:27.221 --> 22:28.222
And so tonight...

22:29.515 --> 22:30.766
you get no bread.

22:30.849 --> 22:32.017
(Bell dings)

22:39.608 --> 22:41.694
Lillian: He must be joking.
Ted: He's joking.

22:41.777 --> 22:42.903
(Guests laugh)

22:43.946 --> 22:46.132
- This is next-level.
- Felicity: How are you not gonna...

22:46.156 --> 22:47.157
Wow, he's not kidding.

22:47.241 --> 22:49.886
Not gonna serve bread at a restaurant
known for their bread. That's sweet.

22:49.910 --> 22:50.953
- What?
- Anne: Thank you.

22:51.829 --> 22:53.747
It's not a fake-out, is it?

22:53.831 --> 22:55.583
- What?
- Ted: No.

22:56.292 --> 22:57.710
It's gotta be a bit.

23:00.004 --> 23:01.046
Are you fuckin' serious?

23:01.505 --> 23:02.631
Slowik: In this spirit,

23:02.715 --> 23:06.552
please enjoy
the unaccompanied accompaniments.

23:07.094 --> 23:09.072
Felicity: "The bread
you will not be eating tonight

23:09.096 --> 23:11.807
"was made from a heritage wheat
called red fife,

23:11.890 --> 23:15.686
"crafted with our partners
at the tehachapi grain project

23:15.769 --> 23:17.521
"devoted to preserving heirloom grains."

23:17.605 --> 23:19.481
- This is insane.
- George: Mmm!

23:20.524 --> 23:23.402
I gotta say that the shit around
the total absence of the bread

23:23.485 --> 23:25.446
is, like, really good.

23:25.821 --> 23:28.073
I mean, it's a little outrageous,
isn't it?

23:28.157 --> 23:30.951
It's fiendish, really.

23:31.452 --> 23:35.122
I mean, he's always been keenly aware
of food as a history of class...

23:35.205 --> 23:36.707
I mean, as have I.

23:36.790 --> 23:37.791
Sure.

23:38.459 --> 23:44.423
Though I will say that this emulsion
does look slightly split.

23:45.007 --> 23:46.008
Ted: Yeah.

23:46.508 --> 23:49.470
I mean, I wasn't gonna say anything.
I noticed as soon as it came down.

23:49.553 --> 23:51.430
It's broken. It's broken.

23:51.764 --> 23:54.391
Yeah, which is really...
I mean, you really...

23:56.477 --> 24:00.064
You really shouldn't see that in
a restaurant of this quality. There it is.

24:00.147 --> 24:01.482
- Well, there it is.
- Yeah.

24:01.565 --> 24:04.860
Oh, my god. I mean,
it's next-level badassery.

24:04.943 --> 24:07.154
The way he weaves in
historical allegories.

24:07.571 --> 24:10.240
I mean, the game is trying to guess
what the overarching theme

24:10.324 --> 24:11.575
of the entire meal is gonna be.

24:11.659 --> 24:12.910
You won't know until the end.

24:13.369 --> 24:15.204
Wait. You... you like this?

24:15.287 --> 24:16.413
Mmm-hmm. Oh, yeah.

24:16.497 --> 24:18.082
He's basically insulting you.

24:18.666 --> 24:20.501
No, no, no. You don't get it.

24:20.584 --> 24:21.627
It's a concept.

24:21.710 --> 24:23.504
I know what a concept is, Tyler.

24:23.587 --> 24:24.963
Trust me. He's telling a story.

24:25.047 --> 24:26.566
That's what makes his food so exciting.

24:26.590 --> 24:29.134
He's not just a chef. He's a storyteller.

24:29.218 --> 24:30.695
And he doesn't give a fuck
about the rules.

24:30.719 --> 24:32.864
Call me the girl next door,
but maybe there are some rules

24:32.888 --> 24:35.307
that you should give a fuck about,
like, I don't know,

24:35.391 --> 24:37.142
giving food to people at a restaurant.

24:38.811 --> 24:42.064
Dearest, no one would ever
call you the girl next door.

24:42.147 --> 24:43.524
Lillian: I make my own bread.

24:43.607 --> 24:45.192
- You do? I didn't know that.
- Yeah.

24:45.275 --> 24:47.194
Oh, yeah. I mean, it's very rustic.

24:47.277 --> 24:49.405
It's peasant style. Yeasty.

24:49.905 --> 24:51.240
What kind of yeast are you using?

24:52.282 --> 24:53.909
Oh, I make my own from apples.

24:53.992 --> 24:56.370
Well, of course you make
your own yeast from apples.

24:57.204 --> 24:59.081
- You wicked thing.
- (Elsa clears throat)

24:59.581 --> 25:01.125
- Elsa: Ms. Bloom?
- Mmm?

25:01.208 --> 25:03.293
Elsa: Here is another broken emulsion.

25:04.169 --> 25:06.088
Courtesy of chef slowik.

25:06.463 --> 25:08.257
(Amusing music playing)

25:11.802 --> 25:12.862
Soren: Hello. Bryce: Excuse me.

25:12.886 --> 25:14.471
Is everything to your liking, sir?

25:14.555 --> 25:17.433
Well, actually, no. Thanks for asking.

25:18.016 --> 25:19.518
Uh, I mean, look, the food's great

25:19.601 --> 25:21.478
and we totally
get all the conceptual stuff.

25:21.562 --> 25:23.397
But could we please get a little bread?

25:23.480 --> 25:25.542
You know, and some gluten-free
for my friend as well?

25:25.566 --> 25:26.686
- No.
- (Amusing music stops)

25:27.484 --> 25:28.485
"No?"

25:29.111 --> 25:30.195
No.

25:30.279 --> 25:31.947
(Chuckles nervously) Okay.

25:32.030 --> 25:35.033
This is all very clever,
and I didn't want to pull this card,

25:35.117 --> 25:38.036
but you know who we are, right?

25:38.871 --> 25:39.872
Yes.

25:40.080 --> 25:42.124
You do? You know who we are?

25:42.458 --> 25:43.459
I know who you are.

25:43.542 --> 25:46.587
Mmm-hmm. Then you know
we work with Doug verrick, right?

25:47.004 --> 25:48.672
No, you work for Mr. Verrick.

25:49.173 --> 25:50.424
- Exactly.
- Oh, fuck it.

25:50.507 --> 25:53.260
And so you know,
we all play on the same team.

25:53.343 --> 25:56.054
So, just slip us a little bread.

25:56.138 --> 25:58.265
- Please.
- We won't tell a soul, lady.

25:58.348 --> 26:00.267
- I promise, okay?
- No.

26:01.435 --> 26:03.228
- (Soren sighs)
- Did you say, "no?"

26:03.687 --> 26:05.189
I said, "no." Yes.

26:05.272 --> 26:06.356
- Okay.
- Okay.

26:06.440 --> 26:07.691
- Wow.
- Okay.

26:08.192 --> 26:09.777
That will be all, though. Thanks.

26:11.195 --> 26:12.196
May I?

26:12.613 --> 26:14.364
You don't have to do... okay.

26:17.493 --> 26:20.078
(Whispering) You will eat
less than you desire

26:20.162 --> 26:21.747
and more than you deserve.

26:24.291 --> 26:25.834
It's a pleasure to serve you.

26:26.794 --> 26:29.338
Ted: Well, I remain in ketosis,
so that's good news.

26:29.797 --> 26:32.549
Tyler: Without the bread,
it really focuses you.

26:32.966 --> 26:35.093
It's so fucking good. Embalm me in this.

26:37.179 --> 26:39.014
- Are you not gonna try it?
- No.

26:39.097 --> 26:40.349
- No?
- No.

26:40.432 --> 26:41.433
This is great stuff.

26:41.517 --> 26:43.602
- I'll take it and eat it.
- Yeah, go for it.

26:43.685 --> 26:45.395
(All gasp)

26:45.938 --> 26:47.258
Tyler: That was a total accident.

26:47.564 --> 26:49.044
Margot: It happens to the best of us.

26:51.652 --> 26:52.736
Tyler: I'm...

26:53.278 --> 26:54.863
I'm sorry. That was...

26:54.947 --> 26:56.156
No, I'm so sorry.

26:59.493 --> 27:00.911
You haven't touched your food.

27:02.079 --> 27:03.205
There...

27:03.288 --> 27:04.665
There is no food.

27:05.249 --> 27:06.917
Well, no. This is food.

27:08.043 --> 27:11.296
So, um, lots more food to come.

27:11.380 --> 27:13.191
- Don't wanna fill up.
- That would not be possible.

27:13.215 --> 27:15.968
I've precisely designed
the portions to account for that.

27:16.051 --> 27:18.136
So, (chuckles) You won't fill up.

27:18.679 --> 27:19.721
Please eat.

27:20.389 --> 27:22.391
The menu only makes sense if you eat.

27:22.474 --> 27:23.767
But you told us not to eat.

27:24.476 --> 27:26.979
That is not what I meant, madam.
And you know it.

27:28.689 --> 27:31.066
Well, thank you for your concern,

27:31.149 --> 27:34.361
but I am perfectly capable
of deciding when I eat and what.

27:39.199 --> 27:40.200
Thank you.

27:42.119 --> 27:43.328
Christ, that was humiliating.

27:43.412 --> 27:44.788
Margot: "Humiliating?"
Tyler: Yeah.

27:44.872 --> 27:46.498
Margot: Tyler, the guy is a prick.

27:46.582 --> 27:47.624
Tyler: Please don't.

27:48.917 --> 27:50.377
You shouldn't be so fucking rude.

27:50.460 --> 27:52.921
Margot: What?
Tyler: He asked you to eat.

27:53.005 --> 27:54.440
Margot: I don't like it.
Tyler: Just try it.

27:54.464 --> 27:55.465
Please.

27:57.342 --> 27:58.677
(Somber music playing)

28:04.975 --> 28:06.685
Plating in three, my friends!

28:06.768 --> 28:07.811
Cooking team: Yes, chef!

28:11.690 --> 28:13.525
(Classical music playing)

28:25.245 --> 28:26.955
(Classical music fades)

28:27.039 --> 28:30.834
Sommelier: That's a 2013
Pinot noir from Ross Cobb.

28:31.209 --> 28:33.295
We hyper-decanted it
with an immersion blender

28:33.378 --> 28:35.172
to awaken it from its slumber.

28:35.255 --> 28:36.256
(Both chuckle)

28:36.340 --> 28:39.426
Slavonian oak, rich cherry
and tobacco notes,

28:39.509 --> 28:43.388
and a faint sense of longing and regret.

28:44.181 --> 28:46.224
- Yes. Enjoy.
- Margot: Longing and regret.

28:46.850 --> 28:47.935
My favorite.

28:52.689 --> 28:54.274
Anne: She's staring again.

28:54.358 --> 28:55.525
Where do we know her from?

28:55.609 --> 28:56.735
We don't.

28:56.818 --> 29:00.155
Well, she really does look like Claire.

29:00.238 --> 29:02.074
Why do you keep saying that? She doesn't.

29:02.950 --> 29:04.076
You don't think so?

29:04.159 --> 29:05.619
She's nothing like our Claire.

29:07.412 --> 29:09.206
That same faraway face.

29:09.289 --> 29:10.958
Can we not obsess? Please?

29:12.125 --> 29:14.920
I know. Hypothetically,
if you were leaving...

29:15.003 --> 29:16.522
- Felicity: Right.
- Which you're not...

29:16.546 --> 29:18.757
- Felicity: Mmm-hmm.
- What would you be leaving for?

29:18.840 --> 29:20.676
Associate development co-exec.

29:21.134 --> 29:22.260
And what the hell is that?

29:22.344 --> 29:27.015
It's in development, so I'd be developing
or helping to develop things...

29:27.099 --> 29:28.701
Why would that be better
than working for me?

29:28.725 --> 29:30.161
Well, because there's a future there.

29:30.185 --> 29:31.645
- It's a corporate...
- Right. Right.

29:31.728 --> 29:33.981
A different kind of future.
Does that make sense?

29:34.064 --> 29:35.065
At the corporate...

29:35.148 --> 29:36.584
Thank god it's all
just hypothetical anyway.

29:36.608 --> 29:37.943
(Slowik claps)

29:38.026 --> 29:40.070
The next course is called "memory."

29:40.529 --> 29:42.239
And that is what it's meant to evoke.

29:42.739 --> 29:43.740
A memory.

29:44.157 --> 29:45.951
So, let me tell you a memory of mine.

29:46.034 --> 29:49.246
When I was growing up,
a child in Waterloo, Iowa,

29:49.329 --> 29:52.040
Tuesday was taco night.

29:52.124 --> 29:53.417
George: Oh, yeah!

29:53.500 --> 29:54.543
Taco Tuesday!

29:54.626 --> 29:56.294
- George: Yeah!
- (Guests laugh)

29:56.378 --> 29:58.714
And this, here, this lady here.

29:58.797 --> 29:59.923
This is my mother.

30:00.007 --> 30:01.550
(Guests exclaim)

30:01.633 --> 30:03.051
As you can see, she's rather drunk.

30:03.635 --> 30:05.846
- (Guests chuckle)
- This is not unusual.

30:06.304 --> 30:07.973
When I was seven years old,

30:08.056 --> 30:11.476
one Tuesday, my father
came home quite drunk.

30:13.061 --> 30:14.062
Really drunk.

30:14.563 --> 30:15.939
Also, not unusual.

30:17.566 --> 30:19.609
My mother grew angry and screamed at him,

30:19.693 --> 30:22.779
at which point,
he proceeded to wrap a telephone cord

30:22.863 --> 30:24.531
around her neck and pull it tight.

30:25.699 --> 30:26.742
I wept.

30:27.325 --> 30:29.369
I screamed, I begged him to stop.

30:29.911 --> 30:30.954
To make him stop,

30:31.788 --> 30:35.459
I finally had to stab him in the thigh
with kitchen scissors.

30:40.005 --> 30:41.506
You remember that, mother, don't you?

30:42.382 --> 30:45.469
Now, I suppose I should've
stabbed him in the throat that evening.

30:45.927 --> 30:48.680
But we're not so smart when we're young.

30:49.598 --> 30:51.183
It was, as you can imagine,

30:52.017 --> 30:54.186
as a very memorable taco night.

30:56.063 --> 30:58.124
- George: Oh, thank god he didn't.
- I mean, what the fuck was that?

30:58.148 --> 30:59.983
- Theatrical.
- Felicity: You liked that?

31:00.067 --> 31:03.320
Yeah, it's a backstory to what
makes him a chef artist.

31:03.945 --> 31:06.406
Dude, that guy's got some
really dark sense of humor, bro.

31:06.490 --> 31:07.850
George: He's such an intense dude.

31:10.202 --> 31:12.412
Slowik: So, here you have

31:13.330 --> 31:16.208
house-smoked bresse
chicken thigh al pastor

31:16.291 --> 31:19.002
and our own tortillas
made with heirloom masa,

31:19.086 --> 31:21.922
- one of hawthorn's signature dishes.
- Thank you.

31:22.005 --> 31:25.175
Slowik: We change our menu constantly,
but, as Ms. Bloom knows,

31:25.258 --> 31:27.677
this has been a staple since day one.

31:28.428 --> 31:30.055
It's what you once said...

31:30.597 --> 31:31.723
Put you on the map.

31:31.807 --> 31:33.100
Slowik: Put me on the map.

31:33.183 --> 31:35.560
Precisely what map would that be...

31:36.103 --> 31:37.145
I wonder.

31:37.229 --> 31:41.274
Anyways, because we're always innovating,
and we fear irrelevance,

31:42.651 --> 31:44.319
an update to a classic.

31:44.402 --> 31:48.824
The images on the tortillas have been made
using a laser-engraving machine.

31:48.907 --> 31:50.267
It's the first time we've used it.

31:51.493 --> 31:55.163
We hope this taco night evokes
strong memories for us all.

31:55.247 --> 31:56.248
Enjoy.

31:57.165 --> 31:58.375
(Lillian chuckles softly)

31:59.835 --> 32:01.920
Well, of course he had to do a taco.

32:02.754 --> 32:03.755
Ted: Here you are.

32:06.049 --> 32:07.050
What are they, lil?

32:07.425 --> 32:08.585
Lillian: They're restaurants.

32:09.886 --> 32:10.887
Um...

32:13.932 --> 32:16.685
That I reviewed that all closed.

32:16.768 --> 32:17.769
Ted: Oh!

32:17.853 --> 32:19.104
Like a gag, then?

32:19.187 --> 32:20.939
Lillian: Um, I think so.

32:21.690 --> 32:22.890
Anne: Richard, what are these?

32:23.942 --> 32:25.819
Taco things. For the tacos.

32:25.902 --> 32:28.822
No, the pictures. They're all of us.

32:32.826 --> 32:36.788
This one is after you had the melanoma
removed from your forehead.

32:36.872 --> 32:37.998
There's the bandage.

32:38.081 --> 32:39.521
Isn't that nice? They remembered us.

32:40.500 --> 32:41.877
Margot: Tyler, is that you?

32:42.711 --> 32:45.046
Yeah. They're all me from tonight
taking fucking photos.

32:45.130 --> 32:47.966
- (Tyler sighs)
- Jesus Christ, what's with this guy?

32:48.049 --> 32:50.093
I knew it. He hates me.

32:50.177 --> 32:52.012
God damn it.
I didn't think he'd really mind.

32:52.095 --> 32:54.598
- Should I apologize?
- Apologize for what?

32:54.681 --> 32:56.641
George: Oh... (Laughs)
Felicity: What?

32:57.976 --> 32:59.227
<i>Calling doctor sunshine.</i>

32:59.728 --> 33:01.897
Oh, my god. I forgot
about that one. (Laughs)

33:01.980 --> 33:03.732
Dumb part. Bad script.

33:03.815 --> 33:04.816
Fun shoot, though.

33:04.900 --> 33:07.777
Hmm. Maybe it's a joke
'cause you're friends, right?

33:08.904 --> 33:10.655
Yeah, yeah, you know, friends.

33:11.364 --> 33:13.450
I mean, you know, do I have any friends?

33:15.243 --> 33:16.661
Soren: Wait. Um...

33:17.204 --> 33:18.644
(Stammers) Hey, guys, what the fuck?

33:20.123 --> 33:21.124
Dave: Are these...

33:22.834 --> 33:23.960
How did they get these?

33:27.339 --> 33:28.381
It's not good.

33:30.217 --> 33:31.676
Bryce: Uh, excuse me.

33:33.720 --> 33:34.721
(Clears throat)

33:35.931 --> 33:37.283
- Can I help you, sir?
- (Clears throat)

33:37.307 --> 33:38.558
Yeah. What...

33:39.267 --> 33:40.644
What the hell are these?

33:40.727 --> 33:42.187
These are tortillas.

33:42.729 --> 33:44.272
(Speaking Spanish)

33:44.356 --> 33:46.274
(In English) Yes, and what are these?

33:46.983 --> 33:48.902
These are tortillas

33:48.985 --> 33:51.780
which contain echobrite's tax records
and other documents,

33:51.863 --> 33:54.908
showing how your company
has created invoices with fake charges.

33:56.117 --> 33:57.244
How did you get these?

33:57.327 --> 34:00.121
I'm sorry, but chef
never reveals his recipes.

34:00.205 --> 34:02.290
(Scoffs) Do you know how fucked you are?

34:02.999 --> 34:05.479
We'll have this place closed
by the morning. Do you understand?

34:05.627 --> 34:08.088
Oh, no, that won't be necessary.

34:09.297 --> 34:10.297
Enjoy.

34:10.590 --> 34:13.092
Anne: And this is you and...

34:15.762 --> 34:16.846
Who is that woman?

34:20.141 --> 34:21.141
Uh...

34:24.521 --> 34:25.563
(Scoffs)

34:26.398 --> 34:28.400
Well, how the hell
should I know? It's faked.

34:28.483 --> 34:31.860
It's some sort of stupid joke.

34:31.945 --> 34:34.281
Soren: It's a fucking taco, okay?
It can't hurt you.

34:34.364 --> 34:36.284
Yeah, a fucking taco
that might hold up in court.

34:36.324 --> 34:40.245
We have plausible deniability,
and if they try to turn us in...

34:40.328 --> 34:41.389
Soren: (Snaps fingers) Right!

34:41.413 --> 34:43.581
If they turn us in,
they'd be turning verrick in.

34:43.665 --> 34:45.309
And then they'd be
just as fucked as we are.

34:45.333 --> 34:46.458
Right? So, we're fine.

34:47.460 --> 34:48.460
Right?

34:50.170 --> 34:51.607
- Yeah, we're good.
- We're fine. Yeah, fuck it.

34:51.630 --> 34:53.525
They can't take your photograph
without your consent. This is insane.

34:53.550 --> 34:55.010
Stop talking and let me think, okay?

34:55.092 --> 34:57.178
I have to make this right somehow.
I have to.

34:57.262 --> 34:58.781
Well, I'll tell you how you make it right.

34:58.805 --> 35:00.765
You send this shit back. Excuse me.

35:01.182 --> 35:03.226
- Excuse me! Sir, hi.
- Hey. Margot! Margot!

35:04.436 --> 35:06.229
Did you just fucking snap at me?

35:06.313 --> 35:08.249
Do you know how long I've been
trying to get a reservation here?

35:08.273 --> 35:09.566
No, and I don't really care.

35:09.649 --> 35:12.110
You do not send shit back
to this kitchen, you child.

35:12.652 --> 35:14.130
You thank them for
even letting you in the door.

35:14.154 --> 35:16.132
- What did you just call me?
- I called you a child

35:16.156 --> 35:17.258
because you're fucking acting like it.

35:17.282 --> 35:19.492
Tyler, you need to apologize
to me right now.

35:19.576 --> 35:20.636
You cannot speak to me that way.

35:20.660 --> 35:23.060
Actually, I can because,
ding dong, I'm the one who's paying.

35:23.121 --> 35:24.539
So maybe, shut up and eat.

35:27.375 --> 35:29.210
Mmm. Oh, my god.

35:31.796 --> 35:32.839
Oh, my god.

35:33.590 --> 35:35.592
This is incredible. You have to try this.

35:35.675 --> 35:38.178
No, thanks. Don't let me interrupt.

35:45.060 --> 35:46.061
Miss mills?

35:47.354 --> 35:48.521
How can I assist you?

35:49.647 --> 35:51.232
Just looking for the ladies' room.

35:51.316 --> 35:52.317
Right this way.

35:54.277 --> 35:55.278
Thank you.

35:56.571 --> 35:57.989
What's behind that silver door?

35:59.157 --> 36:00.283
Something very special.

36:14.130 --> 36:15.131
(Door lock clicks)

36:29.062 --> 36:30.105
(Lighter clicks)

36:33.900 --> 36:35.610
(Door unlocking)

36:35.693 --> 36:36.986
No, you can't...

36:42.283 --> 36:43.535
(Door closes, lock clicks)

36:43.618 --> 36:44.661
You shouldn't be in here.

36:44.953 --> 36:47.372
I'd like to know specifically what it was

36:47.455 --> 36:50.208
about the last course
that you did not enjoy.

36:50.291 --> 36:52.085
You've barely eaten the food.

36:52.168 --> 36:53.169
Why?

36:54.087 --> 36:56.464
I need to know. Why don't you eat?

36:56.714 --> 36:57.757
Why do you care?

36:57.841 --> 37:01.052
I take my work very seriously,
and you're not eating.

37:02.345 --> 37:03.555
And that wounds me.

37:18.445 --> 37:20.780
I guess I'm just not very hungry.

37:22.365 --> 37:23.533
I've told you who I am.

37:23.616 --> 37:26.202
I'm Julian slowik, and I am the chef here.

37:26.286 --> 37:27.662
Now, who are you?

37:29.122 --> 37:33.418
I'll ask again. Who are you?

37:33.501 --> 37:34.669
I'm Margot mills.

37:35.587 --> 37:37.255
So, where are you from, Margot?

37:38.131 --> 37:40.341
I'm from grand island, Nebraska.

37:41.050 --> 37:42.490
Now, does that make you feel better?

37:42.552 --> 37:44.613
You want the address for mom's
trailer park, you asshole?

37:44.637 --> 37:46.723
No, it's not who you want me
to think you are.

37:48.057 --> 37:49.058
Who are you?

37:49.142 --> 37:51.519
I am Margot.

37:53.354 --> 37:54.814
You shouldn't be here tonight.

37:55.732 --> 37:57.442
Please get the fuck out of my way.

38:00.862 --> 38:02.447
(Eerie music playing)

38:08.369 --> 38:10.455
(Door opens, closes)

38:18.087 --> 38:19.881
(Indistinct chatter)

38:25.929 --> 38:27.972
Still very theatrical, but minimalist,

38:28.056 --> 38:29.974
like the Japanese,
the "minimirasuto" style.

38:30.058 --> 38:31.059
(Tense music playing)

38:31.142 --> 38:33.019
Lillian: But he was being playful, right?

38:33.102 --> 38:34.145
Ted: Yes.

38:34.229 --> 38:35.498
Lillian: I mean,
let's talk about the tacos.

38:35.522 --> 38:37.232
It's a dialogue. It's playful.

38:44.030 --> 38:45.031
(Slowik claps)

38:47.283 --> 38:48.451
I'm excited.

38:48.535 --> 38:50.161
We're ready for our next course,

38:50.245 --> 38:52.247
- which I think you'll find...
- Excuse me.

38:52.664 --> 38:54.082
But what the hell is going on here?

38:54.165 --> 38:56.668
Would you just let me finish, please?
That okay?

38:58.086 --> 38:59.087
Thank you.

39:00.588 --> 39:04.926
Ladies and gentlemen,
please meet sous-chef Jeremy louden.

39:05.718 --> 39:07.554
(Clapping)

39:10.098 --> 39:12.475
Jeremy created the next dish.

39:12.559 --> 39:14.936
It's called "the mess."

39:15.687 --> 39:17.855
Originally from sparks, Nevada,

39:17.939 --> 39:21.401
Jeremy studied at the culinary institute
in Hyde park.

39:22.235 --> 39:25.446
Jeremy's goal, as he wrote
in a heartfelt letter,

39:25.530 --> 39:27.907
was to work for me here at hawthorn.

39:29.200 --> 39:30.702
Isn't that right, Jeremy?

39:30.785 --> 39:32.453
- Yes, chef.
- (Clicks tongue)

39:34.289 --> 39:35.832
Jeremy is talented.

39:37.542 --> 39:38.710
He's good.

39:39.294 --> 39:41.462
He's very good. (Sniffles)

39:42.589 --> 39:44.257
(Clicks tongue) But he's not great.

39:45.425 --> 39:47.969
He'll never be great.

39:49.220 --> 39:54.058
He desperately wants
my prestige, my job, my talent.

39:54.976 --> 39:58.396
He aspires to greatness,
but he'll never achieve it.

40:00.690 --> 40:01.691
Correct, Jeremy?

40:02.108 --> 40:03.192
Yes, chef.

40:03.276 --> 40:05.153
Like me at his age,

40:05.236 --> 40:08.615
Jeremy has forsaken everything
to achieve his goals.

40:10.116 --> 40:13.536
Like mine, his life is pressure.

40:14.329 --> 40:16.956
Pressure to put out
the best food in the world.

40:17.749 --> 40:21.753
And even when all goes right,
and the food is perfect,

40:22.378 --> 40:25.256
and the customers are happy,
and the critics are, too,

40:25.340 --> 40:28.134
there is no way to avoid the mess.

40:29.218 --> 40:31.095
The mess you make of your life,

40:31.638 --> 40:34.641
of your body, of your sanity,

40:35.558 --> 40:41.481
by giving everything you have
to pleasing people you will never know.

40:43.149 --> 40:44.150
Jeremy...

40:45.610 --> 40:46.861
do you like this life?

40:46.944 --> 40:48.696
This life that you dreamed about?

40:50.531 --> 40:51.949
- No, chef.
- Mmm-hmm.

40:52.033 --> 40:53.284
And do you want my life?

40:55.203 --> 40:56.996
Not my position, nor my talent.

40:57.080 --> 40:58.081
My life.

41:01.042 --> 41:03.044
No, chef. (Breath trembling)

41:10.718 --> 41:12.011
(Kisses)

41:17.725 --> 41:20.395
Ladies and gentlemen, your fourth course,

41:20.937 --> 41:24.107
- sous-chef Jeremy's the mess.
- (Clapping)

41:26.526 --> 41:29.112
- (Gun fires)
- (Guests scream)

41:32.156 --> 41:33.717
- George: Fuck!
- (Sinister music playing)

41:33.741 --> 41:34.909
Anne: Oh, god!

41:35.493 --> 41:36.536
Soren: What are you doing?

41:38.413 --> 41:39.455
What's wrong with you?

41:40.206 --> 41:41.290
Lillian: The fuck is that?

41:42.959 --> 41:44.711
That was a shock.
I didn't see that comin'.

41:45.336 --> 41:46.379
Soren: What the fuck, man?

41:46.462 --> 41:47.922
Slowik: Please. Sit. Sit.

41:48.005 --> 41:49.233
Sommelier: Everything's fine.
Slowik: Please, it's all fine.

41:49.257 --> 41:51.175
- What happened?
- It's just part of the menu.

41:51.259 --> 41:52.844
- It's part of the show.
- It's a show?

41:52.927 --> 41:54.470
George: That's a show? That's not...

41:54.554 --> 41:56.180
This is what you're paying for.

41:56.264 --> 41:57.449
George: That's a stunt?
(Stutters) What was that?

41:57.473 --> 41:59.726
Slowik: This is an exclusive experience.

41:59.809 --> 42:00.994
- Please just...
- Soren: What the fuck, man?

42:01.018 --> 42:02.103
Return to your seats.

42:02.854 --> 42:04.230
Thank you so much.

42:06.065 --> 42:07.066
Dave: Is he dead?

42:07.150 --> 42:08.544
Felicity: It's definitely
a squib or a packed...

42:08.568 --> 42:09.628
- Stay right there.
- Can I invite you

42:09.652 --> 42:10.921
- to sit down, please?
- Felicity: I've seen them

42:10.945 --> 42:12.505
- use it before.
- Dave: It's not funny.

42:13.156 --> 42:14.198
What the fuck?

42:14.282 --> 42:15.801
- Is this real?
- Bryce: What is happening?

42:15.825 --> 42:18.035
George: It looks so damn real.
Lillian: No, no, no.

42:18.119 --> 42:20.288
This is just theater, right?

42:20.371 --> 42:21.765
Soren: What the fuck
are you talking about, lady?

42:21.789 --> 42:23.249
He just fucking shot himself, okay?

42:23.332 --> 42:25.626
Ted: It looked very real, Lillian.
Quite real.

42:25.710 --> 42:27.962
This is... this is just theater.
It's stagecraft.

42:28.045 --> 42:29.046
Is it really?

42:29.130 --> 42:30.441
Lillian: Yeah. This is what he does.

42:30.465 --> 42:32.091
It's part of the menu.

42:34.385 --> 42:36.512
(Tense music playing)

42:52.028 --> 42:53.154
- Eat!
- (Gasps)

42:57.867 --> 42:59.035
Enjoy.

42:59.118 --> 43:00.453
(Suspenseful music playing)

43:06.501 --> 43:08.252
Fifth course on order.

43:08.336 --> 43:09.545
Cooking team: Yes, chef!

43:11.923 --> 43:13.341
Tyler, what the hell is going on?

43:13.424 --> 43:16.010
Sommelier: And here we have
a biodynamic cabernet franc

43:16.093 --> 43:19.305
from our friends at domaine breton.

43:20.097 --> 43:24.227
It has no added sulfites,
a bit of barnyard funk,

43:24.310 --> 43:28.022
and just a wonderful match
with roasted proteins. Enjoy.

43:28.105 --> 43:30.525
- We're leaving. Now.
- (Stutters) But I have to get my wrap.

43:30.608 --> 43:32.109
- Forget your wrap. Get up.
- But I...

43:32.193 --> 43:33.194
Elsa: Mr. Leibrandt?

43:33.277 --> 43:34.463
- We're leaving.
- Is something wrong?

43:34.487 --> 43:35.530
We're leaving.

43:36.072 --> 43:37.740
There is no boat to leave on.

43:37.824 --> 43:38.991
Then I'll call a helicopter.

43:39.075 --> 43:41.369
That would be very difficult
without phone service.

43:42.245 --> 43:43.246
Fucking move.

43:43.329 --> 43:45.089
Jesus. Just do what they say,
for god's sake!

43:45.122 --> 43:46.749
I'll handle this.

43:46.833 --> 43:49.502
- Just let me handle this.
- With which hand, Mr. Leibrandt?

43:49.585 --> 43:50.628
What?

43:50.711 --> 43:53.548
With which hand will you
handle this? Left or right?

43:53.631 --> 43:55.299
What the fuck are you saying?

43:55.383 --> 43:56.384
Shall we choose?

43:56.968 --> 43:58.052
Richard: Choose what?

43:59.011 --> 44:00.721
Very well. Left hand.

44:01.180 --> 44:02.181
